{"id":1054723,"guid":"D1CCFB22B4FA48EEA1148866C4AA8B52","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"7D28BF5668B44A268989DF390FEA68E5","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>NOD-scid common gamma chain knockout (NOD.Cg-Prkdcscid Il2rgtm1Wjl\/SzJ) (NSG) and NSG-(K<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">b<\/span><span> D<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">b<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;vertical-align:super;\">)<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">null<\/span><span> (IA)<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">null<\/span><span>(NSG MHC KO) mice are obtained from <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.jax.org\/jax-mice-and-services#\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">the Jackson Laboratory<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> or bred in-house and housed in a specific pathogen-free microisolator environment. Adult mice are used at 6\u201310 wk of age. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1194934,"guid":"111D79F0CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","previous_id":1194933,"previous_guid":"EBFEE9B0CAC211EBA83DFF7120B8374A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"2EA27507338644E0812F02574AC0CBDF","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"DEA9465DC02C4C7F8A1F90997C26C640","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Discarded human fetal thymus and liver tissues of gestational age 17\u201320 wk are obtained without identifiers from Advanced Bioscience Resources (ABR, Alameda, CA). Informed consent from women choosing to donate fetal remains for research are obtained by ABR. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1194937,"guid":"2BCD9960CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","previous_id":1194934,"previous_guid":"111D79F0CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"F4F5B61AE9D84C8684D7E29819A66698","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"51872E8B74FD4B8CA4A195734C577365","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Fetal thymus fragments are cryopreserved in 10% dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and 90% human AB serum (<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.rndsystems.com\/atlanta-biologicals-now-rd-systems\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Atlanta Biologicals<\/span><\/a><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">). <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1194939,"guid":"3A1573D0CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","previous_id":1194937,"previous_guid":"2BCD9960CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"0A1B478E0A3D401FA992364FA6C97DC1","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"9349CB8140F64D82A8097D21244769C2","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Fetal livers (FL) are cut into small pieces and incubated in <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">  of <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">  liberase (<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/www.sigmaaldrich.com\/US\/en\/product\/roche\/libtmro\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Liberase\u2122 Research Grade, 05401119001, Roche<\/span><\/a><span><\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">) for 20 minutes in a <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>  CO<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:sub;\">\u00b2<\/span><span> incubator. Every 5-7 minutes, the samples are vortexed and pipetted up and down to facilitate the digestion process. Digested cells are washed and CD34<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span> cells (referred to as HSCs) are positively sorted with magnetic cell sorting (MACS) (Miltenyi Biotec). From each FL, we harvest 10-30 million CD34<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span>cells with a purity of 70-90%. CD34<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span> HSCs are also cryopreserved in 10% DMSO and 90% human AB serum. <\/span><\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"F48A57C0CAC411EBA83DFF7120B8374A","order_id":2,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":5,"unit":"mL","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"FE2B8D80CAC411EBA83DFF7120B8374A","order_id":3,"type_id":25,"title":"concentration","source":{"concentration":0.1,"unit":null,"title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"1B52C770CAC511EBA83DFF7120B8374A","order_id":4,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":37,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1194941,"guid":"56D05760CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","previous_id":1194939,"previous_guid":"3A1573D0CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"B2A915E5F11341D58A52357E439C17D9","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"F0E19D063EEA43A3859E9324C8DB7D17","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Four types of HIS mice can be generated with human FL-derived CD34<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span>HSCs: HIS mice with no thymus, with a native mouse thymus, with a human thymus graft, or with both human and mouse thymi. To generate HIS mice with no thymus, NSG mice are thymectomized and 2 weeks later, sublethaly irradiated (100cGy) and injected i.v. with 1-2x10<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">5<\/span><span> human FL-derived CD34<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span>HSCs. HIS mice with a native mouse thymus are generated similarly, except they were not thymectomized. Similar to the first group, HIS mice with a human thymus graft are thymectomized. Two weeks later, the mice are injected i.v. with HSCs and transplanted with autologous (to human HSCs) human fetal thymus fragments measuring about 1 mm\u00b3 under the kidney capsule. HIS mice with both human and mouse thymi are generated similar to the HIS mice with a human thymus, except they were not thymectomized. <\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1194942,"guid":"5D63B0E0CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","previous_id":1194941,"previous_guid":"56D05760CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"2767B37A9CB94CACAE607DECBD757AEF","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"22CDFDDC483144C8BA03E052488F056D","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">To ensure that pre-existing T cells in the transplanted donor human thymus are not able to persist, we freeze and thaw the thymus tissues and also pipett them up and down several times before transplantation to release as many thymocytes as possible. To further deplete passenger thymocytes that might migrate to the periphery, an anti-human CD2 antibody is injected to the mice in 2 weekly doses (400\u00b5g\/mouse, intraperitoneally). <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1194943,"guid":"759BF280CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","previous_id":1194942,"previous_guid":"5D63B0E0CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"451C29869B3B48B8AE520834B44842FA","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"DA95D15C87E748A4A989D89D263F29C3","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>HIS mice humanized at the neonatal stage are generated by injecting FL HSCs into neonates 1-2 days after birth (intra-liver, 10<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">5 <\/span><span>HSCs in 50\u03bcl PBS injected using a 28-gauge needle). Neonatal mice receive half of the irradiation dose (50cGy) that the adult mice receive (100cGy). <\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1194944,"guid":"836AF370CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","previous_id":1194943,"previous_guid":"759BF280CAC311EBA83DFF7120B8374A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"B76CA42D574943C6A0030A290382A76B","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":""}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"D1FB0865C32340DAB65DAEBF8507748B","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>To generate Personalized Immune (PI) HIS mice with a human thymus graft, thymectomized NSG mice aresublethally irradiated (100cGy) and injected i.v. with 2x10<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">5 <\/span><span>bone marrow (BM)-derived CD34<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">+<\/span><span> HSCs from an adult donor. Two weeks after thymectomy, the mice are transplanted with human fetal thymus fragments (matched to the BM HSCs for a class I and a class II HLA allele) measuring about 1 mm\u00b3 under the kidney capsule. Similar to generation of mice with fetal HSCs, measures are applied to deplete the pre-existing thymus graft-derived T cells. <\/span><\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>This protocol details how to create humanized mouse models from NSG mice. Four different variants of humanized mice can be generated based on whether or not the native thymus is retained or if a human thymus piece is transplanted. Which type of humanized mouse is desired depends on the goals for the experiment. See our protocols on NSG mouse thymectomy, human CD34+ cell isolation, and human fetal thymus preparation for more details on some of the steps in this protocol (\u201c<\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.bvrhn536\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Thymectomy procedure to remove native thymus of NSG mice<\/span><\/a><span>\u201d, \u201c<\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.bvvsn66e\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Human CD34+ cell isolation from fetal liver, and fetal thymus preparation<\/span><\/a><span>\u201d, \u201c<\/span><a href=\"http:\/\/dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.bvswn6fe\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">CD34+ isolation from human bone marrow<\/span><\/a><span>\u201d).<\/span><\/div><br\/><br\/><br\/><br\/><\/div>","changed_on":1632495721}